        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Christian Benesch",
                "href": "/profile/Christian-Benesch"
            },
            "answer_text": "A2A Well I cannot speak for the French, but it seems to me they did not have a really solid foothold in that area. The Mississippi area was enormous. Sooner or later they would have had to cope with the Spanish push north and the American push to the West.  What with a major revolution, a European war to be fought and lack of dominance over the supply routes, is not easy to see how they would have kept these lands. I think it was a very conscious decision to cash in and at the same time to stick it to the Brits. On the whole though it is a bit of a shame. Geopolitics would be much more interesting if the world hadn't turned quite so monolithic after the 7-years war.  ",
